[SN]TITLE[SN]
Seven police given criminal convictions in Wales

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
Five police officers and one police community support officer in north Wales as well as one Dyfed-Powys Police officer have been convicted of offences in the past three years, figures show.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
The convictions include a sex offence, assault, drink-driving and speeding.
Figures for South Wales Police and Gwent Police were not released.
Just 25 of the 45 UK forces responded to Freedom of Information requests by the Press Association, showing 309 officers had convictions.
North Wales Police said, in 2012, a male sergeant was convicted of driving without a licence and while using a mobile phone and a male police officer was convicted of careless driving.
Another police officer was cautioned for a data protection offence.
In 2013, a male police officer was convicted of drink-driving and a female police officer was convicted of assault.
In 2014, a male constable was convicted of a sexual offence and a male police community support officer (PCSO) was convicted of speeding.
The force said 26 serving police officers and four PCSOs had a criminal conviction.
Dyfed-Powys Police said a male police officer was convicted of criminal damage to leisure items in 2012.
South Wales Police and Gwent Police refused the request for information on cost grounds.
